node.text:
This video is from the brilliantly minded Dr Russ Harris, he's a really big name in a therapy called acceptance and commitment therapy, which I can shamelessly say I'm obsessed with. (It works wonders for me and my clients experiencing anxiety, depression, long term health conditions and a bunch more ). So our brains 🧠 have evolved to think negatively in order to keep us safe and alive, that was really really really necessary 1000s of years ago when we were being chased by sabre tooth tigers and stuff, but now... Not so much. Sometimes we think negatively, then get down on ourselves for thinking negatively, making us think even more negatively, You see where I'm going with this ♻️. We need to remember that it's not necessarily our fault that we do this BUT we can decide whether or not we want to continue to do it.

I hope this vid was helpful in explaining how we got here!

Stay tuned for more info tips and tricks ❤️❤️ #motivationmondays

node.text:
Question 2: Where does it come from? Even if the person is talented and super capable why does she develop Imposter Syndrome.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
1. According to the Journal of Multicultural Counseling and Development, one factor stands out above the rest for contributing to IS - discrimination. Discrimination comes in many forms and is bred from judgment. This can be a judgment against race, gender, or any other qualifier that a person “is” or “is not” capable of something.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
2. In their research into women and imposter syndrome, Pauline Rose Clarence and Suzanne Imes found that women face imposter syndrome more frequently and more intensely than men because of family and social constructs that outline how women ‘should be’.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Centuries of western civilisation has created a box for women to be housekeepers, mothers, caregivers, emotional, sensitive and less involved in a career than their male counterparts. This is the social contract that both men and women partake in unconsciously. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
From childhood to middle age, women have been conditioned to have lower expectations for success and achievement, so when a woman is a high achiever, she believes that she is a phoney and that she got lucky. These intense and deep-seated beliefs are the fuel for the furnace of imposter syndrome.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
They propose that successful women who suffer from imposter syndrome also deal with anxiety — because they believe they are breaking the societal and familial mould that was set out for them; they fear that there will be consequences and repercussions.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
* Clarence & Imes, Psychotherapy Theory, Research and Practice (1978), Vol 15, 3.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
That sucks, yes, but this is what My Easy Therapy is ALL about, we’re changing the narrative and getting rid of the imposter syndrome and anxiety that goes with it. ⁠⁠
Hopefully that helps you today.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If you missed the first question in the series, look for the post of me in the yellow dress.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The next post  will be about control. How do I give up some of the control in uncertain situations?

node.text:
Question: How do I relax when I'm not working? I'm always so rushed when I work, I don't seem to be able to relax when I have a day off or during the weekend. I always search for more things to do instead of relaxing.

⬇️

I remember meeting with my supervisor in my first year of clinical training. I was trying to prove myself whilst battling anxiety, on my way to burnout and had severe imposter syndrome (black girl from south east london completing a doctorate in clinical psychology 👀). 

Anyway, I thought she was bonkers. 

She was talking about taking a break, not working weekends, etc, and I was just like 'I've just got this opportunity, and you want me to take time off, what are you talking about? 

By the way, I didn't listen to her the first time around and sorely regretted not taking that time off.

What I didn't understand then, but do now, is that success isn't supposed to come at the expense of your inner peace, success hinges on your inner peace.

In order to get that inner peace, you have to GIVE YOURSELF PERMISSION to prioritise it. The dishes can wait. Your mental health can’t. 

⬇️

1. Tighten your boundaries - A lack of boundaries is really what makes separating work and home much more difficult.
 
2. Find an end of day ritual - Create an obvious “finishing point,” like a post-work trip to the gym, or cup of tea on the way home to create a solid separation between work and home.

3. Practice mindfulness - Without the distractions of the office your mind has less to occupy it. If you notice that you’re lost in negative work related thoughts try @Headspace to bring your mind back to the present moment so you can concentrate on your evening relaxation.

If you were to look at the way you prioritise your emotional and physical wellbeing (yes, even if you're in a busy demanding job), is your setup that of the old Dr Michaela? Or are you willing to believe that you can have the success you really want without feeling like a hamster on a wheel?

Be on the lookout for post number 2... I’m going to tackle...

Where does it come from? Even if the person is talented and super capable why does she develop Imposter Syndrome and/or High Functioning Anxiety?

Do you? Type YES/No in the comments. I can assure you, you aren't the only one my love. Been there, done that, got the T-shirt, binned it. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Over here at My Easy Therapy, things are busy as I get ready to bring a passion project to you.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
This is probably one of the most important things I can do on my mission of supporting women’s mental health and professional success. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Help women manage their high functioning anxiety and imposter syndrome, whilst using their deep thinking and feeling nature to dominate in the workplace. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I mean, what’s the point of working hard to create a good career for yourself, if you’re paralysed by stress, anxiety, burnout, overthinking and self doubt? Because I can’t see it. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
What I do see is ambitious, capable, intellectually fire 🔥, seemingly successful women stuck in mental and emotional hell that’s actually scuppering their chances of the professional progression they know they are capable of. I see this happen time and time again in my clinical practice and I have the tools to do something about it.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
That’s why I’m bringing together THREE things:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
- A FREE 45 minute masterclass ⁠(LINK IN BIO)⁠⁠
- A FREE Instagram series about high functioning anxiety, imposter syndrome, and burnout ⁠(Check the comments section for deets)⁠⁠
- Frozen To Fearless (A paid hands on therapeutic group coaching programme)⁠ LINK IN BIO⁠⁠
⁠⁠
...in an attempt to break the taboo around these topics, and finally get some real answers about what the path looks like from a practically mute, socially anxious, ‘I don’t deserve to be here’ mess...⁠⁠
⁠⁠
➡️ To an internal confidence and self assuredness that garnered a doctorate in Clinical Psychology (Only 3% of people that apply for the doctorate actually make it), a private practice giving me more freedom than I’ve ever had, more invitations for expert guest appearances than I can actually fulfil, a book deal with a MAJOR publisher (thanks Penguin), and an online presence of over 600k followers and beyond…⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And MOST importantly, how that could play out in YOUR PERSONAL self confidence and career progression.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
More deets in the comments section 👇🏾👇🏾👇🏾

Can you relate?⁠

If you’re answer is yes then my friend it’s time to set some boundaries - With others and most importantly with yourself! ⁠
⁠
Let me know in the comments if you’re in need of stricter boundaries around how you spend your time. ⁠
⁠
Burnout is real. The emotional and physical impact of it is real. If you’ve been there you will know that you never, ever want to go back.⁠
⁠
IMO Hustle harder mentality is doing many people a disservice. You need as much internal peace as you can get to be successful and, most importantly, maintain that success. ⁠
⁠
Also, comparison is the thief of joy and the enemy of progress. You need to be in your own perfectly adapted lane. Anything else is someone else’s race. ⁠
⁠
Do you, whatever that looks like. We’re not out here trying to drive ourselves into emotional breakdown because we don’t feel good enough. YOU ARE GOOD ENOUGH. Give yourself a break and you’ll free up some space to show it. I promise.⁠
⁠
Listen ladies, If you consider yourself a high achiever with a strong desire to be successful but feel like:⁠
 ⁠
- you just cannot say no, ever, which leaves you overwhelmed⁠
- You struggle with anxiety ⁠
- Your success or wins are a fluke⁠
- You are never ‘enough’ or can never do ‘enough’ ⁠
- The hamster wheel your on is about to break and chuck you off into a heap on the floor. ⁠
- You can't do much without overanalysing it to death.⁠
⁠
Then sign up for my FREE masterclass - How to Manage High Functioning Anxiety. LINK IN BIO. ⁠
⁠
Get ready for some ‘aha’ moments people.⁠ ⁠
⁠

I’m a highly sensitive person. I love it. I claim the label wholeheartedly. I’ve honed it well and it’s now my superpower. I couldn't imagine getting the results I do for my clients without it. #sorrynotonebitsorry ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
To all the other highly sensitive people out there, never let ANYONE tell you that it’s not a strength. Never let ANYONE tell you the label is problematic (unless you think it is). It’s 2021 and we’re reclaiming the title of HSP. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Thanks to Dr Elaine Aron for your groundbreaking research in this area. The level of understanding I have about what works for me and what doesn’t as a HSP has changed my whole experience of life. Life is just….easier. ⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
To all my successful women struggling with imposter syndrome and/or high functioning anxiety... I know many of you are like damn I’m a HSP too? Well, if you can relate to the info about HSPs then you perhaps (there seems to be a correlation) so it’s definitely worth investigating…⁠⁠⁠
⁠⁠⁠
If you can relate to this post and want to learn how to make life you know...easier then click on the link in bio and sign up to get access to my FREE masterclass How to Manage High Functioning Anxiety and Become a Powerful Presence in The Workplace.  I'll be covering the ins and outs of Imposter Syndrome too! LINK IN BIO⁠⁠

node.text:
Trying to do all the things you need to excel in your career (and keep your bosses happy) whilst managing imposter syndrome, anxiety, and overthinking everything is HARD.
 
I’ve got soooo much actionable info to share on this topic, and I want to make sure that everyone gets a piece.
 
Last week I said to my partner - “Why don’t I just pay it forward and create a free masterclass answering the most common questions I get about high functioning anxiety. So (my fellow) high function anxiety sufferers can:
a. Understand it
b. Get started with managing it even before the Frozen to Fearless programme begins?”.
 
He said, “nooooo, don’t do it”.
 
Just kidding he said “sounds great”....and here we are.
 
Here’s all the juicy topics we’ll cover:
 
- The Difference Between Imposter Syndrome, Depression, High Functioning Anxiety And Just Not Being Good At Your Job + How To Use Your 'Sensitive Nature' To Your Advantage to dominate in the workplace even if you don’t believe you're good enough.
 
- Why Traditional Therapy Isn't Always Best when trying to manage high functioning anxiety (+ what one science backed self help technique is currently turbo charging millennial women's confidence at work).
 
- The 5 Essential Skills You Need to stop your continuous loop of overthinking, approval seeking, self doubt and out of control worry that you’ve had hidden behind a mask of achievements and perfectionism for as long as you can remember.
 
And this ain’t no surface-level stuff either. I’m handing over the processes that I use right now with my clients in my therapy room. 
 
Plus, I’m gonna show you What You’re Getting Wrong When Trying To Manage Your High Functioning Anxiety that keeps it coming back + the danger of dismissing it because you are embarrassed, don’t think it's a real thing, or don’t want to be seen as ‘complaining’.
 
I am so tired of seeing amazing ambitious women with every single skill they need to be super successful in their careers only make it so far because they just don’t believe they truly have what it takes...I've been there, I'm not going back.
 
If you're one of those women, and you're tired too, click the LINK IN BIO

All my love - Dr Michaela

node.text:
Let's nip this in the bud shall we👇🏾👇🏾👇🏾⁠
⁠
🎨@mai⁠siesghost⁠
⁠
As you know, I specialize in supporting ambitious, career oriented (but highly anxious and self critical) women manage their anxiety, imposter syndrome and stay away from burnout. ⁠
⁠
Why?⁠
⁠
- So they can become a powerful presence in their workplace.⁠
- Move up the career ladder without feeling anxious and overwhelmed as soon as they open their eyes in the morning.⁠
- Keep their physical health, and boundaries in check.⁠
- Get that type of freedom that comes with more paper (you know what I'm talking about).⁠
- And make life you know, easier.⁠
⁠
Why else?⁠
⁠
I’m currently preparing for the launch of Frozen To Fearless next week... so stay tuned!⁠
⁠
Through My Easy Therapy I'm on a mission to support at least 10,000 women manage difficult emotions, unhelpful thoughts, ditch imposter syndrome and high functioning anxiety over the next 5 years, so we can claim the success (and freedom) we should have had a LONG time ago. ⁠
⁠
Don't get me started.⁠
⁠⁠
Give me a little “here here” if you’ve ever had one of these thoughts:⁠
⁠
“I know I need to say no to extra work and last minute social plans as it's just too much for me right now, but I don't want to let anyone down”.⁠
⁠
“I’m struggling to stay afloat and I probably do need help but i'm embarrassed as everyone thinks I have it together, and other people have it worse, I can’t mention it”.⁠
⁠
“I accept that no one is perfect when it comes to others but that rule doesn't apply to me”.⁠
⁠
“Jenna shares her ideas clearly and with certainty, and she empowers others, she's got her isht together, I wish I was like that”.⁠
⁠
Your hands up, right? ⁠
⁠
That’s absolutely fine.⁠
⁠
Because trying to do all the things you need to excel in your career (and keep your bosses happy) whilst managing imposter syndrome, anxiety, and overthinking everything is HARD.⁠
⁠
And that’s why I’m legit excited to bring you the brand new down n’ dirty free 45-minute masterclass - How to Manage High Functioning Anxiety + Become a Powerful Presence In Your Workplace (Even If You Struggle To Say Two Words In a Meeting).⁠
⁠
LINK IN BIO ⁠
